\b\fs30 \cf0 Using Bezel\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\pardirnatural

\b0\fs24 \cf0 \
While using Bezel, you might notice that the cursor jumps to the simulator window while you are clicking and dragging on the watch face. This is the puppet-string mechanism that Bezel uses to send clicks on the watch screen to the simulator showing through. Bezel actually sends clicks over to the simulator window much like a screen-sharing application would.\
\
By default, Bezel will update the watch face at a rate of 60 FPS. I\'92ve found that on a relatively recent 13-inch MacBook Pro Retina and a Retina iMac, this has an acceptable amount of CPU use, but you will find that your CPU runs at a differing amount based on how fast it is. There is a submenu in the View menu you can use to alter this frame rate if you find 60 FPS is too demanding for your hardware or you wish to save some on battery life.\
