While I was working on Bezel, I found a blog post by David Smith about Visualizing Watch Apps that dovetailed nicely with my work on the app:\
	{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://david-smith.org/blog/2014/12/01/ailw-visualizing-watch-apps/"}}{\fldrslt http://david-smith.org/blog/2014/12/01/ailw-visualizing-watch-apps/}}\
\
In this, he describes how you can put the simulator window onto your phone running xScope Mirror using Iconfactory\'92s great {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://xscopeapp.com"}}{\fldrslt xScope}} utility on your Mac. This allows viewing the screen at pretty much the size that people expect it to actually be on the real device (assuming it has close to a 326 dpi resolution).\
\
You can use this technique with Bezel by targeting the Bezel window instead of the Simulator. If you have Bezel on a Retina display, you can use the normal 1:1 display mode of xScope, or if you\'92re on a non-Retina display, you can use the Bezel View menu to zoom the watch up to 200%, which allows the 1:1 setting in xScope Mirror to render the watch on a Retina screen with full fidelity.\
